2) Ms Trinh was pleased. 
3) Police reports were filed.


Features of a news article

We've looked at the key features of 
a news article (and their English names).

In the next part of this lesson, 
we are going to take a closer look 
at the style of writing reports and the types of sentences we use.

Here's a reminder of the features and what they mean! 🗒

a headline (n) – 
the large title of a news article usually 
not written in complete sentences

a subtitle (n) – the first sentence of a news 
article that tells the main story

a paragraph (n) – a group of sentences that relate to a topic

a quotation (n) – a statement of what a person 
said (using "quotation marks" to show this)

report writing - news articles, business journals
creative writing - poems, novels, movie scripts

It is claimed the robber stole $2 million worth of diamonds.
You'd expect to read this sentence in a news article.

I was sitting silently in our cold, dimly-lit living room, 
staring intently at my cup of boiling hot, freshly-brewed coffee.
This sentence is very descriptive and personal, like a creative text.

"I could feel the warm glow from the sun on my tired, weathered face."
This is an example of creative writing that is personal and 
uses descriptiveadjectives.

"Dr Beluchi was said to have lost 40% of his patients during his residency."
This reporting sentence is objective and uses statistics.

The passive with "it" for reporting verbs
If you want to use a reporting verb (said, claimed, reported) in the 
passive voice, we can start with the word "it" and use this structure:

It + to be + reporting verb (past participle) + that + sentence
Have a look at the examples below.
It is said that a lack of protein can lead to hair loss.
It was claimed that the divorce settlement exceeded $10 million.
It has been reported that 80% of students miss online learning.

Charges dropped in strawberry needle case
It has been reported that the food contamination case against 
My Ut Trinh was dropped after three years.

The 53-year-old was informed that the trial would no longer go ahead. 
At the time, it was alleged that she had inserted needles 
into strawberries grown in the farm she supervised.

“The prosecution have indicated they would no longer go ahead with the 
charges against you.”, the Crown informed Ms Trinh. It is said that Ms 
Trinh was pleased with the outcome as her lawyer stated, “She thanks 
everyone who believed in her innocence.”

In September 2018, 230 police reports were filed of needle contamination, 
prompting supermarkets to pull their supply of strawberries from their shelves.

Her lawyer stated, “She thanks everyone who believed in her innocence.”
This is a quotation from the lawyer's statement.

It has been reported that the food contamination case against 
My Ut Trinh was dropped after three years.
"It has been reported" is in the passive voice. It does not tell us 
who reported the information.

It is estimated that fruit farmers had lost around $160 million.
"It is estimated" is in the passive voice. It does not tell us 
who provided this information.

Why do we use the passive voice in report writing?
It's used to make our writing more formal and to avoid mentioning the speaker.

She was informed that the trial would not proceed.

Have a look at the text. Which reporting verbs were used?
alleged, informed

