5. Developing fluency - Report news in writing

Listen to an interview with Macau's Minister of Tourism, Henry Tang, 
and complete the dialogue.

Pause
-01:23
Settings
Enter fullscreen
An interview with Macau's Minister of Tourism 🇲🇴 on the impact of the film "Suite Con"

Reporter:
Mr Tang, you’ve heard of hit comedy "Suite Con", a hoax comedy 
where a fake couple trick casinos across Macau into giving them free hotel rooms. 
Would you say your city’s become famous?

Mr Tang:
Oh yes! We’re very excited that our city's gone mainstream. 
The success of Suite Con has led to a tourism boost.

Reporter:
What has been the impact on tourism?

Mr Tang:
All rooms in three of our top hotels are fully booked for the next 24 months. 
Also, some airlines are opening direct flights to Macau for the very first time.

Reporter:
Where will people be able to fly from?

Mr Tang:
Hopefully, the new flights from New York, Dubai and Paris will go ahead as planned. 
Right now, you can only fly direct from 8 countries, so it’s crazy 
what one film can do for a city!

Reporter:
Macau is also known as "The Vegas of the East", but are tourists 
just interested in the casinos?

Mr Tang:
Oh, no, Macau is more than that! Not only did they show all the gentrified areas 
like the Macau Tower, but some scenes take place at Portuguese colonial landmarks 
like the Ruins of St Paul's Church where Jennifer tries a pastel de nata.

Reporter:
Finally, do you think this film will attract copycat criminals 
trying to get free rooms in your hotels?

Mr Tang:
Hahaha! That would be frightening!

Which sentence best summarises the interview with Mr Tang?
Tourism boosts in Macau thanks to comedy hit Suite Con.

Which quote from Mr Tang describes how the film benefitted Macau's tourism?
"All rooms in our top hotels are fully booked."
Tourism has increased as more people are booking hotel rooms in the city.

"Hopefully, the new flights from New York, Dubai and Paris will go ahead as planned."
There aren't any direct flights from these destinations now, but they are planned.

There aren't any direct flights from these destinations now, but they are planned.
Film shows both the modern and historic sights of Macau.

"Don't quote me on that!", she said.
When we want to state exactly what someone's said, 
must use quotation marks, like this → " "

We can include a reporting phrase (a person's name + a reporting verb) 
either before or after the sentence.

