6. Listening to descriptions of heroes - Learn about heroes in "Star Wars"

Some new words 🔍
The video has some "movie-specific" vocabulary (words that are common when 
discussing the world of film). Here are some definitions before we watch:

an editor (n): someone who decides the final content of a movie, book or magazine
montage (n): the technique of creating a scene from pictures, text, or music
a pan (n): a movement of the camera across a horizontal or vertical scene
a layout (n): the way a scene is arranged
ILM (n): Industrial Light & Magic, Lucasfilm’s special effects and animation studio
relatable (adj): you feel an emotional connection with a "relatable" character

The director focuses on the way they filmed this battle scene.

The director focuses on the way they filmed this battle scene.
"Everything is wobbling" (moving unsteadily) is the present continuous.

Do you remember?
We describe scenes and events from films in the present, 
as if what we are describing is happening right now. 
We do this to make the story seem more engaging or dramatic. 🚀

In the video the director is commenting on the scene that we are watching with him. 
Perhaps you noticed that he said things like "you see" and 
"our heroes" to include us in the action.

You can just see everything is wobbling on these things.
They’re...going up against these massive tanks.
...you see she’s scared.
You see once again our heroes don’t have a chance.

They’re going up against these massive tanks.
You can just see everything is wobbling on these things.

You see once again our heroes don’t have a chance.

"So, this is the battle of Crate..."
Unlike the more formal film reviews you wrote in a recent lesson, 
the director's oral description of the battle scene contains many features of informal, 
spoken English, which often don't add meaning to the sentence. 💬

We heard the examples below in the video:

so
Often used to signal the start of a story or explanation.
"So, this is the battle of Crate..."

just
Used for emphasis, with a similar meaning to "simply".
"It just feels like our brave heroes going into battle."

you know
Sometimes used like "um" when thinking about what to say next.
"Because, you know, in a PG 13 Star Wars movie you can’t..."

basically
Used just before an explanation, even if it's not basic!
"They’re in, basically, rolling lawnmowers."

"So, this is all about geography, this big pan here..."
"So" signals the start of a story or explanation.

So last Friday I went so see the new Star Wars movie, 
and I was pleasantly surprised – I really enjoyed it!

Just 👌
The word "just" has various meanings, and in the video the director uses 
it frequently as an adverb (it comes before a verb).

It doesn't change the significance of what he is saying, 
but it has a similar meaning to "simply".

You just want to feel that this is David versus Goliath.
You can just see everything is wobbling on these things.
It just feels like our brave heroes going into battle.

I just love going to the cinema, it's the best way to experience an action film!

Because, you know, in a PG 13 Star Wars movie you can’t really show the violence of a battle.

"They’re in, basically, rolling lawnmowers."
We use "basically" to indicate that we are summarising the most important aspects of something.

Basically, I've been locked out of my house and I need some help.

Here's a tip!
On the next screen we will hear all these expressions in another informal conversation. 👂

The director focuses on the way they filmed this battle scene.

You're a hero! 🦸
You've already learned a lot of new language this lesson.🏅 
To finish the lesson we are going to give our thoughts on heroes.

1) "...even having the open canopies so our heroes feel very exposed, 
and you just want to feel that this is David versus Goliath even them falling apart..."
2) "...when the fighters come and you see once again our heroes 
don’t have a chance, it’s like hawks versus mice."

"...when the fighters come and you see once again our heroes 
don’t have a chance, it’s like hawks versus mice."
A "metaphor" is an image that is representative of something else. 
The "hawks versus mice" represent the fighters against our heroes.

Hawks versus mice 🦅 🐭
The director uses the metaphors of "David and Goliath" and "hawks and mice" 
to emphasise the big challenge the Star Wars heroes are facing in the battle. 
David and Goliath is a story from the Bible about a fight between a man and a giant, 
and, like the image of mice fighting hawks, it represents an uneven fight.

In films and stories, heroes are often represented as the underdog 
(someone who is unlikely to win a fight or competition). This means that 
they feel more relatable to us, and that their success is more impressive.

"And I love this moment with Kelly, it’s so relatable, just it’s a big 
heroic moment, but you see she’s scared, and you see that she takes some 
strength and goes into battle."

If a character is "relatable", we can form an emotional connection to them.

Basically, my favourite heroes in movies or books are those that I can, 
you know, identify with. They have to have human issues, otherwise I can't connect with them.

When you think of a hero, it's usually just the image of a strong warrior 
in battle that comes to mind. But actually, the most heroic characters are 
emotionally vulnerable in some way.

